, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Cadwgan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Cadogan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cadogan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire and Glamorgan) and Irish (of Welsh origin): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Catgucaun</i>, <i>Catguocawn</i>, modernized as <i>Cadwgon</i>. It is composed of <i>cad</i> ‘battle’ + <i>gogawn</i> ‘honour, glory’. See also   Wogan  . The surname is stressed, like its Welsh original, on the penultimate syllable, hence its occasional development to   Duggan  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Ceadagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceadagán</i>’."]}]},{"name":"Iorwerth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>iōr</i>‘ ‘lord’ + a mutated form of <i>berth</i> ‘handsome’; borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by the jealous brother of  Madawg , son of  Maredudd . <i>Iorwerth</i> came to be regarded as a Welsh equivalent of  Edward , but it has no actual connection with that name."],"variants":[{"name":"Yorath","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Iorwerth   or, in some cases, a transferred use of the surname derived from it."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Iorwerth ap Cadwgan was born in 1060, in Wales as the son of Cadwgan ap Elystan Glodrydd. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"1060–":"1060–Surnud","1055–Male":"1055–Surnud","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1020–Male":"1020–Surnud","1090":"1090","1055":"1055","1020":"1020","1060":"1060","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"1060–":"1060–Kuollut","1055–Male":"1055–Kuollut","1060–Male":"1060–Kuollut","1090–Male":"1090–Kuollut","1020–Male":"1020–Kuollut","1090":"1090","1055":"1055","1020":"1020","1060":"1060","Wales":"Wales"},"fr":{"1060–":"1060–Décédé","1055–Male":"1055–Décédé","1060–Male":"10